00:06:49,943 --> 00:06:53,624
And I'm sure we all receive email after a milestone,

164
00:06:53,684 --> 00:06:56,585
after a playtest, after when we ship a season,

165
00:06:56,645 --> 00:06:57,326
or something like that.

166
00:06:57,746 --> 00:07:00,187
And it's 100 pages with a lot of boards and graphs.

167
00:07:00,227 --> 00:07:03,928
And I'm sure everyone is reading them, like missing nothing.

168
00:07:03,948 --> 00:07:06,069
And they are sure, like, yeah, I get it.

169
00:07:06,189 --> 00:07:06,449
I get it.

170
00:07:06,509 --> 00:07:07,969
I know exactly what happened in my game.

171
00:07:08,089 --> 00:07:08,970
I read all those emails.

172
00:07:09,890 --> 00:07:11,891
Are you really sure that you read them well

173
00:07:11,911 --> 00:07:12,611
and there is no issue?

174
00:07:13,705 --> 00:07:16,946
Well, you know, like, as analysts, most of the time,

175
00:07:17,286 --> 00:07:19,787
we have, or we used to have, game designers coming to us

176
00:07:19,847 --> 00:07:22,427
saying, OK, we want a report with that data.

177
00:07:22,447 --> 00:07:24,548
We want to follow the operator's win rate

178
00:07:25,068 --> 00:07:26,268
through the seasons and everything.

179
00:07:26,868 --> 00:07:29,569
So you make that report, because you know they ask you something

180
00:07:29,589 --> 00:07:30,569
so you're happy to have them.

181
00:07:31,069 --> 00:07:34,490
But sometimes the report is not what they try to,

182
00:07:35,250 --> 00:07:37,871
it's not answering the question they want an answer for.

183
00:07:38,551 --> 00:07:40,251
A good example of that is Frost.

184
00:07:40,752 --> 00:07:43,452
So Frost was our first DLC operator.

185
00:07:43,552 --> 00:07:46,573
She came out like three months after the game released.

186
00:07:47,613 --> 00:07:51,274
And at the time, we had basic reports for the game design

187
00:07:51,294 --> 00:07:51,534
team.

188
00:07:52,154 --> 00:07:56,055
And people were not happy because they were saying,

189
00:07:56,075 --> 00:07:57,135
like, Frost is overpowered.

190
00:07:57,155 --> 00:07:58,295
Like, she's way too strong.

191
00:07:58,916 --> 00:08:01,776
And when we looked at the report, it was the case.

192
00:08:01,836 --> 00:08:04,617
Like, Frost's win ratio was the highest

193
00:08:04,817 --> 00:08:05,937
of all the defending operators.

194
00:08:07,182 --> 00:08:10,324
And so your basic intuition might be to say, well,

195
00:08:11,165 --> 00:08:13,066
the winner ratio is actually a good representation

196
00:08:13,306 --> 00:08:15,308
of the power level of an operator.

197
00:08:16,088 --> 00:08:17,209
But I'd like to show you something

198
00:08:17,669 --> 00:08:20,231
when we digged as analysts a bit more into that data.

199
00:08:21,552 --> 00:08:24,253
So what we wanted to check was whether this operator was

200
00:08:24,313 --> 00:08:27,115
good for new players versus advanced players.

201
00:08:27,135 --> 00:08:28,536
So we took the data that we had before.

202
00:08:28,977 --> 00:08:31,358
We split the population into four different categories.

203
00:08:32,299 --> 00:08:34,280
And so we had beginner players.

204
00:08:35,397 --> 00:08:37,998
For which we saw that, OK, Frost is not the best operator

205
00:08:38,038 --> 00:08:40,499
because she wins less than Rook.

206
00:08:40,759 --> 00:08:43,340
So if you play the game, you know

207
00:08:43,380 --> 00:08:46,801
that Rook is an operator that just drops a bag of armor plates

208
00:08:46,841 --> 00:08:47,601
at the beginning of the round.

209
00:08:48,021 --> 00:08:50,162
And Frost is laying down traps around the map.

210
00:08:50,402 --> 00:08:52,782
So you know that when you're playing Frost,

211
00:08:52,842 --> 00:08:53,963
you need to have good map knowledge.

212
00:08:53,983 --> 00:08:56,444
You need to know where to put these traps and everything.

213
00:08:56,484 --> 00:08:59,525
Whereas when you're playing Rook, you just drop your bag

214
00:08:59,605 --> 00:09:00,005
and you're done.

215
00:09:00,425 --> 00:09:01,885
You've done your job, basically.

216
00:09:02,802 --> 00:09:05,143
So we're like, OK, it makes sense.

217
00:09:05,163 --> 00:09:08,005
So we are going to look at advanced players, so a player

218
00:09:08,065 --> 00:09:10,006
who spent a bit more time in the game.

219
00:09:10,226 --> 00:09:11,387
And it was the case as well.

220
00:09:11,967 --> 00:09:14,408
Like for these players, Rook was winning more than Frost.

221
00:09:14,448 --> 00:09:16,890
So we're like, OK, so obviously Frost

222
00:09:17,430 --> 00:09:18,771
is an operator for advanced players.

223
00:09:20,171 --> 00:09:22,653
But the fact is that when you split your data

224
00:09:22,913 --> 00:09:25,194
across your whole population, this is what you get.

225
00:09:26,168 --> 00:09:28,508
meaning that for all levels of play,

226
00:09:28,869 --> 00:09:30,089
Rook was winning more than Frost.

227
00:09:30,749 --> 00:09:33,090
And this is the exact same data split

228
00:09:33,310 --> 00:09:35,530
into four different subpopulations.

229
00:09:36,691 --> 00:09:41,952
So if you're used to work with data,

230
00:09:42,132 --> 00:09:45,193
this is something that is known as the Simpson's paradox.

231
00:09:45,573 --> 00:09:46,173
So you can look it up.

232
00:09:47,125 --> 00:09:51,149
But the explanation behind that is actually not that hard.

233
00:09:51,229 --> 00:09:53,691
Because if you're looking at the win rates

234
00:09:53,831 --> 00:09:55,552
for the different populations, you

235
00:09:55,572 --> 00:09:59,295
can see that advanced players win more than beginner players.

236
00:09:59,876 --> 00:10:01,697
Like overall, whether it's with Frost or Rook.

237
00:10:02,538 --> 00:10:04,720
And the thing is that Frost is a DLC operator.

238
00:10:04,900 --> 00:10:07,382
So to get her, you need to have a season pass

239
00:10:07,542 --> 00:10:09,643
or to have spent a lot of time in the game grinding

240
00:10:09,704 --> 00:10:11,785
some soft currency to get that operator.

241
00:10:12,926 --> 00:10:15,147
So when we looked at pick rates for these populations

242
00:10:15,167 --> 00:10:17,888
for the two operators, you could see that Frost

243
00:10:18,248 --> 00:10:21,169
was picked a lot more by advanced players

244
00:10:21,989 --> 00:10:23,049
rather than new players.

245
00:10:23,810 --> 00:10:25,370
So what explained these win rates

246
00:10:25,470 --> 00:10:28,791
was not the fact that Frost was better than Rook.

247
00:10:28,991 --> 00:10:32,213
It was the fact that Frost was played by better players,

248
00:10:32,853 --> 00:10:35,574
meaning that this metric is basically useless in terms

249
00:10:35,614 --> 00:10:36,334
of power balancing.

250
00:10:36,734 --> 00:10:39,795
It just shows you if an operator is more played by good players

251
00:10:39,835 --> 00:10:40,015
or not.

252
00:10:41,507 --> 00:10:45,410
So this is where we started to show to game designers that,

253
00:10:45,490 --> 00:10:48,733
OK, you guys, you need to be careful when you're asking

254
00:10:48,773 --> 00:10:50,334
for data, when you're reading your data.

255
00:10:51,555 --> 00:10:53,197
So this is one of the many examples

